<subSubSection pageId="57" pageNumber="58" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="57.[151,1437,1474,1967]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1690,1715]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species belongs to the 
<taxonomicName box="[643,777,1691,1715]" class="Insecta" family="Simuliidae" genus="Simulium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ruficorne">
<emphasis box="[643,777,1691,1715]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">S. ruficorne</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group, and is characterized by the unique female and male genitalia, pupal gill with six filaments and larval head capsule with bold head spots (Takaoka 
<number box="[1307,1368,1727,1751]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" value="2003.0">2003</number>
). This is the only autogenous species in the Oriental Region, of which the female can develop the first batch of eggs without blood-meals (
<bibRefCitation author="Takaoka" box="[395,672,1798,1823]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" refString="Takaoka, H. &amp; Noda, S. (1979) Autogeny of the black fly Simulium (Eusimulium) aureohirtum (Diptera: Simuliidae). Journal of Medical Entomology, 15, 183 - 184. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1093 / jmedent / 15.2.183" type="journal article" year="1979">
Takaoka and Noda 
<number box="[612,672,1799,1823]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" value="1979.0">1979</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). The pupae and larvae of this species appear to be highly adapted to relatively high water temperatures, slow flow and even somewhat muddy or contaminated waters, where most other simuliid species do not occur (Takaoka 
<number box="[660,721,1871,1895]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" value="2003.0">2003</number>
). As noted previously (
<bibRefCitation author="Takaoka" box="[979,1217,1870,1895]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" refString="Takaoka, H., Sofian-Azirun, M., Ya'cob, Z., Chen, C. D., Lau, K. W. &amp; Pham, H. T. (2014 c) New species and records of black flies (Diptera: Simuliidae) from Vinh Phuc Province, Vietnam. Zootaxa, 3838 (3), 347 - 366. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3838.3.6" type="journal article" year="2014" yearSuffix="c">
Takaoka 
<emphasis box="[1082,1130,1870,1894]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number box="[1145,1205,1871,1895]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" value="2014.0">2014</number>
c
</bibRefCitation>
), these capabilities, together with other factors, may explain why this species is widely distributed in the Oriental Region and extends into the Palearctic and Australasian Regions.
</paragraph>
